Repercussion of Bullying in Thirteen Reasons Why
	âThe Butterfly Effectâ means that small things may influence much larger things in a larger scale. As the saying goes, a butterflyâs wing can cause a tornado thousands of kilometers away. A small event may have unexpected catastrophic consequences. Thirteen Reasons Why written by Jay Asher is about a bullied girl named Hannah who committed suicide.  She recorded thirteen tapes about all the things that her classmates did to her that ultimately resulted in her suicide, each for one reason and one person that caused her suicide. The plot showed the theme of bullying very well, as a girl is bullied to death in the story. This is similar to the saying I mentioned above, but the tornado is emotional instead of physical. The book showed how small and unintended actions from peers can cause serious damage to otherâs feelings, in this story, even death.  The author used three main elements to express the theme of repercussion in the story, the joke, the rape, and a heavy use of emotional appeal. 
	First, the author used a small joke to show how unintended small things can become bigger and bigger, which is often seen in bullying. Bullies often think what they do isnât very serious and itâs just a joke. But most of the time these little âjokesâ would hurt the bullied personâs feelings. Taking Justinâs joke as an example. Justinâs unintended joke had an immense effect on Hannahâs story, and can be seen as the start of her catastrophic high school life. Hannah had her first kiss with Justin, at first she thought it was pure and innocent. But Justin started to brag and exaggerate. This small joke caused a huge chain reaction, it made Hannah a sex object for the class. Many students began to have an impression that Hannah is an âeasyâ girl. Many harassments from classmates came, graver each time. At the end Hannah was even raped. This event chain showed how a small and unintended joke can snowball into something much bigger.  The author stated the theme of repercussion in bullying with this sentence, âa rumor based on a kiss started a reputation that other people believed in and reacted to  a snowball effect.â(145). He used the word snowball effect to describe that the start of this event was pretty small, but the consequence is huge. It started just because a teenager wants to brag about his âachievementâ , but it resulted in a girlâs suicide. The joke caused a series of event that ultimately led to the rape in a party. âIf time was string connecting all of your stories, that party would be the point where everything knots up. And that knot keeps growing and growing, getting more and more tangled, dragging the rest of your stories into it.â(239) This sentence also stated that all these small events may combine and cause a huge wave that might eventually destroy someoneâs life.  The joke started the snowball that eventually killed Hannah. The author used this to represent the idea of repercussion in bullying.
	Secondly, Jay Asher used rape to show how victims suffer from bullies who want the pleasure from power, domination, and control. Bullies often bully people because they feel good having total command over somebody else. For example, the worst bully in the story, Bryce is successful in every perspective, his family is rich, he is very popular, he is a good athlete, therefore he thinks that he can do what ever he wants without consequences. In the story he raped two girls, and probably many more unmentioned victims. Hannah was devastated by that rape, both physically and psychologically. âThe night was over. I was doneâ(267). The author described the Hannahâs emotion after being raped with two simple sentences, but they were powerful enough to make the readers feel how defeated she was. âI fell on my knees, sick, covering my mouth with both hands. I stumbled toward the closet, tears blurring the light from the hallâ(265). This is a more physical description of her state, the readers can feel how desperate she was through the actions described in this sentence. The author used rape to show how victims suffer both psychologically and physically from bullies who only want pleasure. 
	Last but not least, the author used lots of emotional appeal in this book. For example, the author used a dead person to narrate a large part of the story. All of the anecdotes of Hannahâs misery was from the tapes that she recorded before her death. It benefits the book not only because first-person narration is more emotional, but also because the voice of the dead would be a constant reminder to the readers that everything they are hearing somehow contributed to her death. As most of the story is narrated by the victim herself, we would be able to read the feelings and emotions of her. Hearing the voice of a suicided person can be very creepy, the tapes were so heavy that the main character, Clay, often couldnât bear to hear it. Another emotional appeal that the author used was this sentence. âWe all could have stopped it. We all could have stopped something. The rumors. The rape. You [Hannah]â (246). This sentence stated that all the people in the story could have helped Hannah and eventually saving her from suicide. This causes the readers to feel guilt, as there may be things that we could but didnât stop, so we could relate to the story easily.  The author used emotional appeals through out the book to make the readers sympathize with the character in the story.
	In conclusion, the author used Justinâs joke, the car accident, and various emotional appeals to show the theme of bullying. Justinâs joke was used to show how small and unintended things could snowball and cause catastrophe. The rapes were used by the author to show how victims can suffer from the bullyâs  arrogant actions. Finally, lots of emotional appeals were used to strengthen the readerâs impression of the theme of repercussion.
